    rationale='The glucose is 55 mg/dL with adrenergic and neuroglycopenic symptoms. If the client is awake and able to swallow safely, the priority is 15 grams of fast-acting oral carbohydrate, followed by repeat glucose assessment.',
    deep_rationale='Hypoglycemia causes both autonomic symptoms, such as shakiness and sweating, and neuroglycopenic symptoms, such as confusion, because the brain depends on circulating glucose. A glucose of 55 mg/dL is clinically significant and needs immediate correction before a dietary-history review or routine teaching. Oral fast-acting carbohydrate is the least invasive and appropriate first intervention when the client is awake and can swallow safely. Glucagon is reserved for severe hypoglycemia when the client is unconscious, having a seizure, or unable to take oral carbohydrate. IV dextrose is also appropriate when oral intake is unsafe or IV rescue is needed, but this option is more invasive than oral carbohydrate for a client who can swallow. Clinical pearl: treat the low first, reassess in about 15 minutes, and never give oral carbohydrate to a client who cannot protect the airway.',
    references_json='[{"title":"NIDDK - Low Blood Glucose (Hypoglycemia)","citation":"NIDDK guidance describes taking 15 to 20 grams of glucose or carbohydrate right away when blood glucose is below target, and discussing glucagon use for emergencies."},{"title":"Endotext, NCBI Bookshelf - Hypoglycemia","citation":"Endotext describes oral glucose or carbohydrate when the patient is able to ingest carbohydrates, with glucagon used in appropriate severe or outpatient rescue situations."},{"title":"NCSBN 2026 NCLEX-RN Test Plan","citation":"NCSBN 2026 RN Test Plan, Pharmacological and Parenteral Therapies and Clinical Judgment."}]',
    deep_rationale_authored_at=unixepoch(),
